WEBVTT

00:02.570 --> 00:04.269
FOX:
For nearly 300 years,

00:04.271 --> 00:06.238
the Vikings were
one of the most brutal

00:06.240 --> 00:09.808
and feared armies
in the history of the world.

00:09.810 --> 00:13.445
Some say their military prowess
was a gift from the gods.

00:13.447 --> 00:15.581
Others say it came from
their unrivaled skills

00:15.583 --> 00:17.783
on the battlefield.

00:17.785 --> 00:19.518
But new controversial evidence

00:19.520 --> 00:22.121
points to another source
altogether.

00:22.123 --> 00:23.956
This has been
unprecedented.

00:23.958 --> 00:26.692
Was the fearsome Viking army
so powerful...

00:28.996 --> 00:30.396
FOX: It's crazy.

00:30.398 --> 00:32.498
FOX: ...because women
were warriors, too?

00:34.468 --> 00:38.804
I'm going on a journey back
1,300 years to Viking times...

00:38.806 --> 00:42.808
It's like a really cool
"Game of Thrones" set.

00:42.810 --> 00:44.877
FOX: ...through historical
Norse texts...

00:44.879 --> 00:48.247
It looks like Merlin.

00:48.249 --> 00:50.449
FOX:
...actual Viking remains...

00:50.451 --> 00:54.753
This is the richest
Viking Age grave ever found.

00:54.755 --> 00:56.021
Wow.

00:56.023 --> 00:58.957
FOX:
...and Scandinavian magic...

01:02.496 --> 01:03.996
...to uncover the truth...

01:06.667 --> 01:09.068
...of Viking women warriors.

01:09.070 --> 01:11.270
And this forces us
to rewrite everything

01:11.272 --> 01:14.173
that we thought we knew
about all ancient cultures.

01:16.610 --> 01:19.044
All across the world,
our ancient ancestors

01:19.046 --> 01:22.381
left behind towering mysteries
and enchanting myths.

01:22.383 --> 01:24.750
That looks like
a magic wand.

01:24.752 --> 01:26.552
As an actress,
I've been lucky enough

01:26.554 --> 01:29.655
to peek behind the curtain
at some of these ancient sites.

01:29.657 --> 01:31.790
I've never been
in a crypt before.

01:31.792 --> 01:34.827
FOX: And it's ignited
an insatiable curiosity in me

01:34.829 --> 01:37.162
to know more about
these lost worlds...

01:37.164 --> 01:38.797
FOX: It's amazing
that under our feet,

01:38.799 --> 01:40.399
there's so much history.

01:40.401 --> 01:42.334
FOX: ...some of which
are still buried

01:42.336 --> 01:44.103
deep in our distant past.

01:44.105 --> 01:45.804
That is amazing.

01:45.806 --> 01:54.346
♪♪

01:54.348 --> 02:02.955
♪♪

02:02.957 --> 02:05.924
This looks really beautiful.

02:05.926 --> 02:08.494
And then there's also all this
incredible archeology

02:08.496 --> 02:09.895
in, like, every direction.

02:09.897 --> 02:11.663
Just pick a spot, start digging,

02:11.665 --> 02:15.367
and you'll find
something amazing.

02:15.369 --> 02:18.170
I've traveled to the small town
of Borre, Norway,

02:18.172 --> 02:22.074
a land of misty fjords
and unspoiled beauty.

02:22.076 --> 02:25.277
But over 1,000 years ago,
this was a center of power

02:25.279 --> 02:27.613
and influence
for the Viking empire.

02:27.615 --> 02:31.483
♪♪

02:31.485 --> 02:34.486
There's much written about
Viking legend and lore,

02:34.488 --> 02:36.989
but in actuality,
we know very little about

02:36.991 --> 02:39.158
who they were
and how they lived.

02:39.160 --> 02:42.895
♪♪

02:42.897 --> 02:45.464
Megan.
So nice to meet you.
Great to meet you.

02:45.466 --> 02:47.799
FOX: So I'm at
the Midgard vikingsenter

02:47.801 --> 02:49.434
to meet Marianne Moen,

02:49.436 --> 02:52.404
an archeologist who has
dedicated her professional life

02:52.406 --> 02:55.941
to deciphering the mysteries
of the Viking people.

02:55.943 --> 02:57.543
So, we're here at
the reproduction

02:57.545 --> 03:00.078
of what we think a chieftain's
hall would have looked like.

03:00.080 --> 03:03.048
So it's not
your average house.

03:03.050 --> 03:04.249
This is where
the chieftains would have

03:04.251 --> 03:06.785
shown off their wealth
and their power.

03:06.787 --> 03:08.787
At this site,
archeologists have studied

03:08.789 --> 03:11.924
thousands of Viking artifacts
to try to reconstruct

03:11.926 --> 03:14.526
how this mysterious people
would have lived.

03:14.528 --> 03:23.969
♪♪

03:23.971 --> 03:26.939
Like a really cool
"Game of Thrones" set.

03:26.941 --> 03:28.140
It really is, actually.

03:28.142 --> 03:29.942
You're quite right.

03:31.545 --> 03:32.878
Everything
that you see here

03:32.880 --> 03:35.414
is more or less reconstructed
or based on

03:35.416 --> 03:38.517
archeologically found
artifacts.

03:38.519 --> 03:40.886
FOX: What was
the Viking Age like?

03:40.888 --> 03:44.723
So, the Viking Age comes
at around about 750,

03:44.725 --> 03:47.459
and it finishes
about 1050.

03:47.461 --> 03:50.729
In the Viking heartland,
it's a fairly peaceful society.

03:50.731 --> 03:52.798
But then you get the view
of the Vikings abroad,

03:52.800 --> 03:54.166
and it's a completely
different story.

03:58.372 --> 04:00.572
Well, if you're trying
to conquer a land,

04:00.574 --> 04:04.209
I mean, it's hard to do that
in a kind, gentle way.
Yes!

04:04.211 --> 04:06.345
Yeah, it really is,
isn't it?

04:06.347 --> 04:10.182
FOX: For 300 years,
from 750 to 1050 A.D.,

04:10.184 --> 04:12.851
the Vikings were arguably
the most feared

04:12.853 --> 04:15.621
and powerful army
in the world.

04:15.623 --> 04:17.956
They began as
small Scandinavian tribes

04:17.958 --> 04:20.325
that banded together
to raid towns,

04:20.327 --> 04:23.228
but by 793,
their power had grown,

04:23.230 --> 04:25.163
conquering the island
of Lindisfarne

04:25.165 --> 04:27.866
off the coast
of modern-day England.

04:27.868 --> 04:29.935
Their success on the battlefield
centered around

04:29.937 --> 04:31.436
their ambush tactics

04:31.438 --> 04:34.606
and the use of thousands
of advanced longships.

04:34.608 --> 04:36.775
These boats could sail
deep oceans,

04:36.777 --> 04:39.645
as well as rivers
as shallow as three feet,

04:39.647 --> 04:42.981
allowing the Vikings to launch
surprise amphibious attacks

04:42.983 --> 04:45.484
on wealthy waterfront targets.

04:45.486 --> 04:46.818
At the height of their power,

04:46.820 --> 04:48.387
the Vikings controlled
settlements

04:48.389 --> 04:51.123
in over 50 of today's
modern countries,

04:51.125 --> 04:55.260
from Newfoundland
to Europe to Russia.

04:55.262 --> 05:00.165
In total, the Viking territory
stretched more than 5,500 miles.

05:00.167 --> 05:03.168
That's larger than
the Roman Empire.

05:03.170 --> 05:06.271
I think when most people
think of the Vikings...
Mm-hmm.

05:06.273 --> 05:07.706
...myself included,

05:07.708 --> 05:11.243
we picture
a very patriarchal society.

05:11.245 --> 05:13.211
-Yeah.
-Do you agree with that?

05:13.213 --> 05:14.713
When you talk about
the Viking Age,

05:14.715 --> 05:18.250
a lot of people have this idea
that women ruled the inside

05:18.252 --> 05:20.452
and that men basically
ruled everything else.

05:30.764 --> 05:32.531
FOX:
Just a few months ago,

05:32.533 --> 05:35.801
a Viking warrior grave
in Birka, Sweden,

05:35.803 --> 05:38.470
first discovered in 1889,

05:38.472 --> 05:41.807
underwent state-of-the-art
DNA analysis,

05:41.809 --> 05:46.278
and the results have set
the archeological world ablaze.

05:46.280 --> 05:47.946
This is the Birka grave?
-Yeah.

05:47.948 --> 05:51.850
The Birka warrior is
fascinating in so many ways.

05:51.852 --> 05:53.352
What is the most
interesting thing

05:53.354 --> 05:56.121
is that it contains things
that indicates military rank

05:56.123 --> 05:58.290
that are pretty much
purely associated with

05:58.292 --> 05:59.391
a male typical burial.

05:59.393 --> 06:02.861
So, you have your sword,
and you have your ax.

06:02.863 --> 06:06.698
There are arrows in here.
There are shields.

06:06.700 --> 06:08.900
So, this was talked about
and written about

06:08.902 --> 06:11.870
as a male grave
for well over a century.

06:11.872 --> 06:14.306
People spoke about it being
a typical example

06:14.308 --> 06:17.242
of a very high-status warrior
at this town,

06:17.244 --> 06:19.878
until last year when
the DNA study was published,

06:19.880 --> 06:23.115
and it turns out to have been
a woman all along.

06:23.117 --> 06:28.487
♪♪

06:28.489 --> 06:32.457
For an archeologist,
this has been unprecedented.

06:32.459 --> 06:34.893
FOX: For centuries, many have
believed that Viking women

06:34.895 --> 06:37.829
were merely
subservient housewives.

06:37.831 --> 06:40.365
But is it possible
that the ferocious Viking army

06:40.367 --> 06:43.068
had women warriors
in its ranks?

06:43.070 --> 06:45.537
It is now a fact that
this person is a woman.

06:45.539 --> 06:48.306
What you do with that
and where you go with
the interpretation --

06:48.308 --> 06:50.509
that's what
the open question is.

06:50.511 --> 06:52.411
It brought out such
strong feelings in people

06:52.413 --> 06:55.147
who so much wanted this
to be a female warrior,

06:55.149 --> 06:56.748
and then it brought out
such strong feelings

06:56.750 --> 06:59.985
in those who really didn't want
her to be a female warrior.

06:59.987 --> 07:02.687
FOX: These new findings have
sparked a massive debate

07:02.689 --> 07:04.322
among archeologists,

07:04.324 --> 07:06.124
with some insisting
that just because

07:06.126 --> 07:08.193
this woman was buried
with weapons,

07:08.195 --> 07:10.228
it doesn't mean
that she actually used them

07:10.230 --> 07:11.596
on the battlefield.

07:11.598 --> 07:15.600
What is the likelihood of
these weapons were gifts

07:15.602 --> 07:18.570
from a husband or things
that she had inherited?

07:18.572 --> 07:19.805
Personally,
I don't think so

07:19.807 --> 07:22.207
because there is
nothing else here,

07:22.209 --> 07:24.142
so that would be that
her entire identify

07:24.144 --> 07:25.644
is made up
of her husband's.

07:25.646 --> 07:26.878
-Her husband.
-Yeah.

07:26.880 --> 07:28.747
So I think a very interesting
placement of that body

07:28.749 --> 07:31.216
in sort of communication
with the rest of the grave.

07:31.218 --> 07:34.953
Well, yeah, the sword is on
either side of her hands...
Yeah. Yeah.

07:34.955 --> 07:37.122
...where she would put them up
if she was gonna use them.

07:37.124 --> 07:39.391
Exactly, exactly.

07:39.393 --> 07:43.028
Why do you think
it's so controversial?

07:43.030 --> 07:44.629
One of the main objections
is that, you know,

07:44.631 --> 07:46.631
she wouldn't have been able
to use her weaponry.

07:46.633 --> 07:49.034
We have women in the military
now that carry those guns...

07:49.036 --> 07:50.402
Oh, yes.
...that are about
50 to 80 pounds.

07:50.404 --> 07:52.037
Exactly.
Just because you're small

07:52.039 --> 07:53.305
doesn't mean
you can't be strong.

07:53.307 --> 07:54.573
-Do you have a husband?
-Yeah.

07:54.575 --> 07:56.308
Have you ever been
mad enough at him

07:56.310 --> 07:57.909
that you could
swing a sword?

07:57.911 --> 08:00.011
-Every day. [ Laughs ]
-Right?

08:00.013 --> 08:01.947
I know.
I'm a small person.

08:01.949 --> 08:04.082
Brian's a lucky man
we don't have those

08:04.084 --> 08:05.617
laying around the house.
[ Laughs ]

08:07.154 --> 08:09.120
FOX:
If there were female warriors,

08:09.122 --> 08:11.389
then centuries
of well-established history

08:11.391 --> 08:13.592
that says the Vikings
were an archaic culture

08:13.594 --> 08:17.329
with rudimentary gender roles
would be shattered.

08:17.331 --> 08:19.631
And that would force us
to rewrite everything

08:19.633 --> 08:22.100
we thought we knew
about the Viking culture

08:22.102 --> 08:25.136
and possibly about
all ancient cultures.

08:25.138 --> 08:31.376
♪♪

08:31.378 --> 08:35.280
But solving this 1,300-year-old
puzzle won't be easy.

08:35.282 --> 08:37.282
It's about finding
the bread crumbs

08:37.284 --> 08:38.850
and connecting them.

08:38.852 --> 08:42.354
So I'm heading to a small island
50 miles off the coast of Sweden

08:42.356 --> 08:45.891
where an active archeological
dig is currently unfolding.

08:47.427 --> 08:48.927
Dan?

08:48.929 --> 08:52.264
Hi. Megan.
How are you?

08:52.266 --> 08:55.867
FOX: Dan Carlsson is
the site's lead archeologist.

08:55.869 --> 08:58.336
His recent discovery of
Viking graves on the island

08:58.338 --> 08:59.738
could be the key

08:59.740 --> 09:01.907
to putting these
centuries-old pieces together.

09:03.911 --> 09:05.777
FOX: How many graves
do you think are here?

09:09.416 --> 09:10.549
Mm-hmm.

09:17.157 --> 09:19.190
FOX: Of the dozens of graves
in the area,

09:19.192 --> 09:21.226
Dan is excavating nine of them,

09:21.228 --> 09:24.930
and he's determined that all of
them hold the remains of women.

09:27.267 --> 09:29.367
Yeah, yeah, please.

09:29.369 --> 09:31.002
FOX: Hundreds of artifacts
were discovered

09:31.004 --> 09:32.304
in these female graves,

09:32.306 --> 09:34.406
which provide
an unprecedented look

09:34.408 --> 09:36.441
into the lives
of Viking women.

09:41.214 --> 09:42.914
Okay.

09:42.916 --> 09:44.382
Okay.

09:48.722 --> 09:49.921
Okay.

09:51.391 --> 09:52.657
Yeah.

09:55.629 --> 09:56.861
Wow.

09:59.666 --> 10:00.765
Yeah.

10:02.569 --> 10:04.603
This is?

10:04.605 --> 10:06.671
Wow.

10:06.673 --> 10:09.274
It's cool
to get to hold it.

10:09.276 --> 10:10.442
[ Laughing ]

10:22.322 --> 10:24.689
What is this?

10:24.691 --> 10:26.858
It looks like magic.

10:29.830 --> 10:32.130
Yeah.
That's amazing.

10:32.132 --> 10:34.966
So, this comes from where?

10:34.968 --> 10:38.036
Mm. So that's evidence
of trade, obviously.
Yeah.

10:42.175 --> 10:45.176
FOX: The Vikings were not only
brilliant on the battlefield,

10:45.178 --> 10:47.445
they were also
shrewd businessmen,

10:47.447 --> 10:49.280
setting of sophisticated
trade routes

10:49.282 --> 10:53.351
stretching through Europe, Asia,
and the Middle East --

10:53.353 --> 10:56.321
trade route riches and resources
to build the ships and weapons

10:56.323 --> 11:00.125
necessary to keep
their war machine running,

11:00.127 --> 11:01.893
Dan and his team
have also uncovered

11:01.895 --> 11:05.363
hundreds of thousands
of silver coins on this island

11:05.365 --> 11:07.866
from as far away
as the Middle East,

11:07.868 --> 11:10.735
suggesting that Gotland would
have been an extremely wealthy

11:10.737 --> 11:12.604
Viking trading center,

11:12.606 --> 11:16.107
connecting goods from the east
and Viking money from the west.

11:24.418 --> 11:26.084
Yeah.

11:26.086 --> 11:27.352
No.

11:27.354 --> 11:30.188
It feels like
a bullet, almost.

11:30.190 --> 11:32.691
Oh, it's a weight?

11:32.693 --> 11:34.192
For a scale.

11:44.938 --> 11:47.238
Yeah.

11:47.240 --> 11:49.641
Yeah. So she was
maybe a merchant.

11:51.411 --> 11:52.644
Yeah.

11:55.649 --> 11:57.515
FOX: Viking women were
supposed to be at home

11:57.517 --> 11:59.384
tending to their families.

11:59.386 --> 12:01.453
But now, here's evidence
that they could have been

12:01.455 --> 12:04.422
traveling the world
as financial power players,

12:04.424 --> 12:06.024
keeping the Viking coffers
filled

12:06.026 --> 12:08.626
for more pillaging and conquest.

12:08.628 --> 12:10.929
Was being a merchant
and a trader --

12:10.931 --> 12:12.163
was that typically
thought of

12:12.165 --> 12:16.334
as a male occupation
or thing to do?

12:16.336 --> 12:18.136
You have to sort of
guess or assume

12:18.138 --> 12:20.972
to a certain point to connect
the dots in archeology,

12:20.974 --> 12:23.341
so why do you think the theory
that there could have been

12:23.343 --> 12:25.777
a Viking female warrior
is so outrageous?

12:25.779 --> 12:28.113
Because it doesn't require
any more guesswork

12:28.115 --> 12:30.281
than any of
this other stuff does.

12:35.889 --> 12:37.055
Yeah.

12:38.825 --> 12:39.924
Right.

12:45.565 --> 12:46.965
Yeah.

12:46.967 --> 12:49.834
FOX: If Viking women were
traveling the world as traders,

12:49.836 --> 12:51.569
they weren't just homemakers.

12:51.571 --> 12:53.605
They served a central
and critical role

12:53.607 --> 12:56.541
in financing one of
the most revered fighting forces

12:56.543 --> 12:58.376
in Europe.

12:58.378 --> 13:01.946
So, Viking women worked
to support the war efforts.

13:01.948 --> 13:04.783
But could they actually
have fought in those wars?

13:04.785 --> 13:08.753
♪♪

13:08.755 --> 13:11.790
We're actually getting
special access today.
Wow.

13:11.792 --> 13:15.894
This is the richest
Viking Age grave ever found.

13:15.896 --> 13:18.930
Wow.
That is amazing.

13:29.676 --> 13:30.975
FOX:
The recent discovery

13:30.977 --> 13:32.777
that a Viking warrior grave
in Birka, Sweden,

13:32.779 --> 13:34.946
actually contains a woman

13:34.948 --> 13:38.550
has generated
an archeological firestorm.

13:38.552 --> 13:40.885
For centuries, Viking women
were believed to be

13:40.887 --> 13:44.756
not much more
than subservient housewives.

13:44.758 --> 13:47.692
But is possible that
1,300 years ago,

13:47.694 --> 13:51.796
the ferocious Viking army had
female warriors in its ranks?

13:51.798 --> 13:56.534
♪♪

13:56.536 --> 13:57.702
Hi.
-Hi.

13:57.704 --> 13:59.137
-How are you?
-I'm good. How are you?

13:59.139 --> 14:00.572
Good.

14:00.574 --> 14:02.340
FOX:
I'm meeting Leszek Gardela,

14:02.342 --> 14:04.676
a leading expert
on Viking burials.

14:04.678 --> 14:09.214
Today we'll get to see a lot
of exciting Viking stuff.

14:09.216 --> 14:12.083
We're actually getting
special access today.

14:12.085 --> 14:15.553
I was wondering why we were
coming in through the back way.

14:17.824 --> 14:19.357
Look to your right.

14:19.359 --> 14:21.292
-To my right?
-Yep.

14:21.294 --> 14:23.294
Wow.

14:23.296 --> 14:26.731
-So...
-That is amazing.

14:26.733 --> 14:32.403
♪♪

14:32.405 --> 14:35.440
FOX: Although first excavated
in 1904,

14:35.442 --> 14:38.343
this Viking burial discovered
65 miles away

14:38.345 --> 14:40.044
in Oseberg, Norway,

14:40.046 --> 14:42.680
is still helping archeologists
answer questions

14:42.682 --> 14:44.382
about the Vikings.

14:44.384 --> 14:48.753
This is the richest
Viking Age grave ever found.
Wow.

14:48.755 --> 14:50.054
This was in a grave?

14:50.056 --> 14:51.222
This is a grave.

14:51.224 --> 14:53.191
The entire ship
was under the ground?

14:53.193 --> 14:55.460
The entire ship was
underground,

14:55.462 --> 14:57.795
buried under
a burial mound,

14:57.797 --> 15:01.633
and containing numerous,
numerous objects.

15:01.635 --> 15:03.935
Amazing.

15:03.937 --> 15:05.470
FOX:
Viking burials like this,

15:05.472 --> 15:08.139
where the dead were sent to the
afterlife inside their ships,

15:08.141 --> 15:11.309
were reserved for the most
important members of society,

15:11.311 --> 15:16.347
like kings, nobles,
and highly decorated warriors.

15:16.349 --> 15:18.116
Commoners were either cremated

15:18.118 --> 15:21.252
or buried with their belongings
under a mound of earth.

15:23.623 --> 15:27.592
The ship is definitely a symbol
of power and prominence.

15:27.594 --> 15:31.129
It is something
that commands respect.

15:31.131 --> 15:33.731
Someone who was given
a burial like this

15:33.733 --> 15:36.067
must have been someone
really, very, very important.

15:36.069 --> 15:37.802
-Mm-hmm.
-But guess what?

15:37.804 --> 15:38.970
What?

15:38.972 --> 15:42.573
This is also
a female grave.

15:42.575 --> 15:45.209
A female was buried
with this massive ship?

15:45.211 --> 15:49.047
Actually, two women
were found onboard.

15:49.049 --> 15:53.017
FOX: The two women buried
in this ship died in 834 A.D.,

15:53.019 --> 15:56.888
one at 80 years old
and the other at about 50.

15:56.890 --> 15:58.723
These are from the grave?
-From the grave.

15:58.725 --> 16:01.359
-She wore those shoes?
-Yep.

16:01.361 --> 16:04.162
FOX: That's amazing.
I don't know why that --

16:04.164 --> 16:06.564
I guess 'cause it's
so human all of a sudden.

16:06.566 --> 16:08.900
You see someone had
their feet in those shoes.
Yeah.

16:08.902 --> 16:10.401
It's really amazing.

16:10.403 --> 16:12.904
What is the theory of why
there were two women inside?

16:12.906 --> 16:14.172
Various theories.

16:14.174 --> 16:16.674
The original theory
was that one of them

16:16.676 --> 16:18.242
was someone
really powerful

16:18.244 --> 16:23.281
and that the younger woman
was perhaps her servant.

16:23.283 --> 16:25.850
And today a lot of people
are thinking that perhaps

16:25.852 --> 16:29.854
both women were of equal status,
of equal importance.

16:29.856 --> 16:33.424
But we don't know exactly
how and why they died.

16:33.426 --> 16:36.627
♪♪

16:36.629 --> 16:38.963
FOX: The key to understanding
who these women were

16:38.965 --> 16:40.798
and why they were so important

16:40.800 --> 16:43.101
lies not only
in how they were buried,

16:43.103 --> 16:44.969
but what they were buried with.

16:44.971 --> 16:47.605
[ Beeping ]

16:47.607 --> 16:49.407
-Please, after you.
-Thank you.

16:49.409 --> 16:52.076
FOX: Leszek takes me to
the rare-artifacts section,

16:52.078 --> 16:55.680
where belongings from the burial
are kept under lock and key.

16:55.682 --> 16:57.081
Do you know
what we're about to see?

16:57.083 --> 16:58.316
-I do.
-Oh, okay.

16:58.318 --> 16:59.584
-Do you?
-No, I have no idea.

16:59.586 --> 17:02.520
-You'll find out in a second.
-Is it a snake?

17:04.924 --> 17:11.829
♪♪

17:11.831 --> 17:14.599
Wow.
-Yes.

17:14.601 --> 17:17.101
That looks like
a magic wand.

17:17.103 --> 17:19.670
It's like Professor Snape's
wand from "Harry Potter."

17:19.672 --> 17:22.240
Mm, of course. Or like
Gandalf's staff if you --

17:22.242 --> 17:24.575
Or like Gandalf's staff,
yeah.

17:24.577 --> 17:25.777
How old is this?

17:25.779 --> 17:29.247
This is
1,000 years old.

17:29.249 --> 17:31.249
-It's made out of iron?
-Yes.

17:31.251 --> 17:32.884
You can see there are
different details

17:32.886 --> 17:34.719
that are still preserved.

17:34.721 --> 17:38.523
FOX: Magical staffs are
all over pop culture today.

17:38.525 --> 17:42.393
But there are references that
go back as far as 2,000 B.C.,

17:42.395 --> 17:44.395
with the tales of priests
in ancient Persia

17:44.397 --> 17:48.399
using bunches of sticks to
connect to the spiritual realm.

17:48.401 --> 17:50.368
2,500 years later,

17:50.370 --> 17:54.038
the Vikings were also
no strangers to conjuring magic.

17:54.040 --> 17:57.341
They were rumored to use
pieces of wood called runes

17:57.343 --> 18:01.345
to predict the future
and to heal the sick.

18:01.347 --> 18:04.315
Don't you wonder who
the first person was to decide

18:04.317 --> 18:08.252
that there was something
magical about a staff and why?
Hmm.

18:08.254 --> 18:11.956
And maybe there<i> was</i> something
magical about that first staff,

18:11.958 --> 18:15.560
because they believed it
for centuries and centuries.
Yeah.

18:15.562 --> 18:18.463
Even in the story of Moses,
he cast down his staff,

18:18.465 --> 18:21.099
it turns into a snake,
and it eats the other snake.
Absolutely.

18:21.101 --> 18:22.867
Of course, it is
definitely something

18:22.869 --> 18:27.205
that was an emblem
of great power.

18:27.207 --> 18:29.841
FOX: This magical staff was
clearly very important

18:29.843 --> 18:32.276
to the Viking women
buried with it.

18:32.278 --> 18:35.113
But exactly what kind of
powerful rituals

18:35.115 --> 18:37.148
could they carry out with it?

18:37.150 --> 18:38.850
There seems to be
this idea

18:38.852 --> 18:41.319
that these
ritual practitioners

18:41.321 --> 18:44.622
were involved in warfare
in one way or another,

18:44.624 --> 18:48.793
either perhaps providing some
form of supernatural protection.

18:48.795 --> 18:52.997
That's cool.
Of course, know about the
<i> barsark,</i> or the berserkers.

18:52.999 --> 18:54.365
What were the berserkers?

18:54.367 --> 18:57.368
The berserkers --
they are described as warriors,

18:57.370 --> 19:00.905
fearless warriors,
who could not be hurt.

19:00.907 --> 19:03.174
FOX: Berserkers were champion
Viking warriors

19:03.176 --> 19:05.676
who fought in a trace-like fury.

19:05.678 --> 19:08.679
This is where the English
word "berserk" comes from.

19:08.681 --> 19:11.415
To enter this
war-frenzy state,

19:11.417 --> 19:15.219
they would take these
special substances.

19:15.221 --> 19:18.856
So there definitely are
very strong aspects of magic

19:18.858 --> 19:21.025
used for warfare.

19:21.027 --> 19:24.595
So it's possible that these
two women were buried like kings

19:24.597 --> 19:27.031
because they had mastered
a type of magic

19:27.033 --> 19:29.534
that gave them unrivaled power
on the battlefield.

19:29.536 --> 19:32.236
And, of course, archeology
is extremely dynamic...
Yeah.

19:32.238 --> 19:35.973
...so people keep finding
new things all the time.
Right.

19:35.975 --> 19:37.708
FOX: So, were these
two Viking women,

19:37.710 --> 19:41.445
in fact, champion warriors?

19:41.447 --> 19:43.014
And is there a bigger story

19:43.016 --> 19:45.616
that their bones and scepters
are telling us?

19:45.618 --> 19:49.554
♪♪

19:57.397 --> 20:00.364
♪♪

20:00.366 --> 20:02.600
FOX: Did the ferocious
and powerful Viking army

20:02.602 --> 20:04.569
have female warriors
in its ranks?

20:04.571 --> 20:09.707
♪♪

20:09.709 --> 20:12.543
Or were women rarely more than
subservient housewives,

20:12.545 --> 20:15.012
like the history books tell us?

20:15.014 --> 20:17.114
I'm turning to
Norse oral traditions

20:17.116 --> 20:21.686
to try and let Viking women
speak for themselves.

20:21.688 --> 20:23.321
KVILHAUG:
The mythology of people --

20:23.323 --> 20:26.757
they reflect on their attitudes,
their ideals,

20:26.759 --> 20:30.328
and to some extent also
the world in which they lived.

20:30.330 --> 20:35.166
Did the myths
actually reflect reality?
Yeah.

20:35.168 --> 20:38.269
FOX: Maria Kvilhaug is one of
Norway's leading experts

20:38.271 --> 20:39.704
on Norse mythology.

20:39.706 --> 20:43.307
She has a near-supernatural
grasp on the "Poetic Eddas,"

20:43.309 --> 20:44.642
a collection of Viking myths

20:44.644 --> 20:47.545
orally passed down
from generation to generation

20:47.547 --> 20:50.615
and finally written down
in the 13th century.

20:50.617 --> 20:53.184
What god was actually
the most important varied,

20:53.186 --> 20:56.754
so each tribe had
slightly different gods

20:56.756 --> 21:01.158
that they paid more attention
to than the others.

21:01.160 --> 21:03.594
Viking myths,
like the story of Thor,

21:03.596 --> 21:06.063
the god of thunder
who slayed giants,

21:06.065 --> 21:09.066
or Odin, the god of war who
sacrificed his right right eye

21:09.068 --> 21:10.935
to drink from
the Well of Knowledge,

21:10.937 --> 21:13.437
are still powerful legends
today.

21:13.439 --> 21:15.806
But in the hundreds of pages
of the "Eddas"

21:15.808 --> 21:19.543
that mention dozens of gods,
kings, and legendary warriors,

21:19.545 --> 21:24.181
there is one striking trend that
sets Viking mythology apart.

21:25.551 --> 21:29.387
Most of the myths that
we know from the Viking Age,

21:29.389 --> 21:34.558
female are just as powerful
in Norse myths as the male.
Mm-hmm.

21:34.560 --> 21:36.927
Women -- they could take
leading roles,

21:36.929 --> 21:39.230
and we see that
in the mythology.

21:39.232 --> 21:40.898
These warrior women --
those women who

21:40.900 --> 21:43.234
do pick up arms
and they do fight --

21:43.236 --> 21:45.936
they're sometimes called
shield-maidens.

21:45.938 --> 21:48.139
FOX: The shield-maidens
of Norse mythology

21:48.141 --> 21:52.343
are as ferocious and powerful
as their male counterparts,

21:52.345 --> 21:54.578
from Hervor, who avenged
her father's death

21:54.580 --> 21:57.682
by leading Viking raids
on a haunted island,

21:57.684 --> 21:59.116
to Lagertha,

21:59.118 --> 22:04.455
who fought alongside Viking
kings in Sweden and Norway.

22:04.457 --> 22:07.692
And the legends
of powerful Viking women

22:07.694 --> 22:10.027
go all the way to the top.

22:19.906 --> 22:21.072
Ahh.

22:25.411 --> 22:27.545
FOX: The Volva is one of
the most important figures

22:27.547 --> 22:29.447
in Norse mythology.

22:29.449 --> 22:32.116
She used powerful magic
to see the future,

22:32.118 --> 22:34.952
and even Odin turned to her
for critical advice.

22:36.989 --> 22:40.725
Not only is the Volva on the
Mount Rushmore of Viking gods,

22:40.727 --> 22:43.728
but she also spawned a real-life
class of Viking women.

22:43.730 --> 22:46.464
♪♪

22:46.466 --> 22:47.965
[ Indistinct singing ]

22:47.967 --> 22:50.034
I'll follow you.
You lead the way.

22:50.036 --> 22:54.872
[ Singing continues ]

22:54.874 --> 22:57.007
FOX: I'm visiting a group
of Viking historians

22:57.009 --> 22:59.343
who live like this class
of ancient women

22:59.345 --> 23:01.979
as a way to try
to understand them.

23:01.981 --> 23:03.981
[ Drumming and
indistinct chanting ]

23:03.983 --> 23:06.117
[ Horn blows ]

23:08.087 --> 23:09.019
[ Applause ]

23:09.021 --> 23:10.287
That was awesome.

23:10.289 --> 23:11.856
Thank you.

23:30.476 --> 23:33.144
FOX: This class of women,
also known as seeresses,

23:33.146 --> 23:36.013
were rumored to channel
the power of their ancestors

23:36.015 --> 23:40.251
to predict the future
and to conjure magic.

23:40.253 --> 23:43.053
They were in such high demand
that they would be lavished

23:43.055 --> 23:46.056
with gifts
in exchange for their powers.

23:46.058 --> 23:49.326
So much for women just being
subservient housewives.

23:49.328 --> 23:52.930
Our ancestors in the past
were in a lot of ways

23:52.932 --> 23:55.933
more progressive
than we are right now.

23:55.935 --> 24:01.772
♪♪

24:01.774 --> 24:04.341
Deep in the forest
of Tomter, Norway,

24:04.343 --> 24:06.110
the Volva women
have arranged for me

24:06.112 --> 24:09.180
to take part in
one of their ancient rituals.

24:10.750 --> 24:13.217
FOX: There's no, like,
dark spirits or anything

24:13.219 --> 24:15.019
we're calling in?

24:19.325 --> 24:22.493
FOX: Maria Jacobsen is
a modern-day seeress

24:22.495 --> 24:25.796
that practices the traditions
of Viking magic.

24:50.523 --> 24:53.691
Maria will guide me
in a ritual called utiseta,

24:53.693 --> 24:55.493
which means "sitting out."

24:55.495 --> 24:59.497
It's the Viking version
of a vision quest.

24:59.499 --> 25:01.599
The seeresses would sit out
in the forest

25:01.601 --> 25:03.734
overnight in solitude,

25:03.736 --> 25:05.669
and by entering
a trace-like state,

25:05.671 --> 25:07.671
they could channel
the spirits of nature

25:07.673 --> 25:09.473
and their ancestral magic.

25:09.475 --> 25:12.877
♪♪

25:12.879 --> 25:17.114
Some say magic is just science
that we don't understand yet.

25:17.116 --> 25:19.850
For me, like,
I believe in magic.

25:19.852 --> 25:21.986
I have a need
to believe in magic.

25:21.988 --> 25:23.888
It gets into my bones.

25:28.728 --> 25:29.894
Okay.

25:33.666 --> 25:35.099
One of them is
my grandmother,

25:35.101 --> 25:36.734
so I know
she's here right now.

25:36.736 --> 25:41.772
♪♪

25:41.774 --> 25:45.009
FOX:
I'll wait for the sun to go down

25:45.011 --> 25:47.912
and then find
a spot in the forest,

25:47.914 --> 25:49.513
and in that quiet,
try to connect

25:49.515 --> 25:51.615
to the power of my ancestors

25:51.617 --> 25:53.817
and the nature spirits
around me.

26:02.161 --> 26:03.761
It's gonna alter
<i> my</i> consciousness

26:03.763 --> 26:07.364
because, like, I sleep with
a light on in my hotel room...
Yeah.

26:07.366 --> 26:08.699
...'cause I'm scared...
Yeah.

26:08.701 --> 26:10.267
...'cause
I'm really sensitive

26:10.269 --> 26:13.370
to energies and spirits
and things like that.

26:13.372 --> 26:16.373
And so I would<i> never</i> go out
into the forest alone.

26:16.375 --> 26:17.908
No.

26:19.478 --> 26:21.078
FOX:
It's getting dark.

26:23.049 --> 26:25.282
I'm scared of the dark.
I'm scared of forests.

26:25.284 --> 26:27.618
I'm scared of being alone.

26:27.620 --> 26:29.486
I'm scared of a lot of things.

26:29.488 --> 26:34.224
I mean, on a scale of 1 to 10
of on a terror scale,

26:34.226 --> 26:37.628
I'm at about a 7,
creeping towards an 8.

26:37.630 --> 26:43.200
♪♪

26:43.202 --> 26:44.501
Okay.

26:44.503 --> 26:46.170
And as soon as you guys
start to trickle away,

26:46.172 --> 26:48.706
it's gonna go up to a hard 10,

26:48.708 --> 26:50.674
and then I don't know.

26:50.676 --> 26:53.143
Nanny, are you with me?

26:53.145 --> 26:56.413
All of my spirit guides,
stay close to me, be with me.

26:57.817 --> 26:59.617
Oh, man.

27:07.059 --> 27:12.262
♪♪

27:12.264 --> 27:15.499
All of my spirit guides,
stay close to me, be with me.

27:15.501 --> 27:17.101
[ Sniffs ]

27:17.103 --> 27:19.203
FOX:
I'm on a Viking vision quest

27:19.205 --> 27:21.972
deep in the Norwegian forest.

27:21.974 --> 27:25.743
It's an ancient practice carried
out by powerful female sorcerers

27:25.745 --> 27:28.512
who were rumored to channel
the power of their ancestors

27:28.514 --> 27:31.248
to predict the future
and to conjure magic.

27:31.250 --> 27:36.086
♪♪

27:36.088 --> 27:38.088
[ Exhales ]

27:38.090 --> 27:47.464
♪♪

27:47.466 --> 27:56.807
♪♪

27:56.809 --> 28:00.511
After hours of complete
isolation in pure darkness,

28:00.513 --> 28:02.279
my quest is complete.

28:02.281 --> 28:06.483
♪♪

28:06.485 --> 28:09.353
-So, you did it.
-I did do it.

28:09.355 --> 28:12.156
♪♪

28:12.158 --> 28:15.025
FOX: I wasn't as scared as
I thought I was gonna be.

28:16.629 --> 28:19.329
It made me very present
to my own emotions

28:19.331 --> 28:21.465
and I think put me
in touch with people

28:21.467 --> 28:23.901
that had been there
maybe thousands of years ago,

28:23.903 --> 28:27.171
but I felt like I was feeling
and receiving

28:27.173 --> 28:28.439
a lot of different energy.

28:28.441 --> 28:31.542
It wasn't necessarily
all my own.

28:31.544 --> 28:34.411
I don't know about being able
to see the future,

28:34.413 --> 28:37.981
but I definitely felt
some power in these woods.

28:37.983 --> 28:39.950
But when it comes to determining
whether women

28:39.952 --> 28:42.553
could actually have been
full-on warriors,

28:42.555 --> 28:46.090
the Vikings didn't make
finding the truth easy.

28:46.092 --> 28:49.460
They left behind literally
no written records.

28:49.462 --> 28:52.062
But other cultures may have.

28:52.064 --> 28:55.833
So I'm heading to the National
Library of Norway in Oslo.

28:55.835 --> 28:59.503
It houses some of
the rarest books in the world.

28:59.505 --> 29:00.604
Hi.

29:00.606 --> 29:01.839
-How are you, Megan?
-How are you?

29:01.841 --> 29:03.340
-Hi. I'm Kim.
-Nice to meet you.

29:04.343 --> 29:06.110
Awesome.

29:06.112 --> 29:07.845
FOX: Kim Hjardar is
one of the world's

29:07.847 --> 29:12.015
most prolific historians
on Viking warfare.

29:12.017 --> 29:15.319
He's gotten me unprecedented
access to a selection of texts

29:15.321 --> 29:17.688
that could help
piece together the past.

29:31.270 --> 29:34.037
By 1090, the Vikings had
expanded their empire

29:34.039 --> 29:36.206
into parts of modern-day Italy,

29:36.208 --> 29:39.443
leading to clashes
with the Eastern Roman Empire,

29:39.445 --> 29:41.311
known as the Byzantines.

29:41.313 --> 29:43.714
This is a chronicle
of a Viking loss.

30:06.405 --> 30:08.305
Mm-hmm.

30:08.307 --> 30:09.873
Of course.
Of course.

30:11.710 --> 30:12.843
Yeah.

30:18.584 --> 30:20.551
FOX: All those scholars
are still debating

30:20.553 --> 30:22.352
the meaning of this account.

30:22.354 --> 30:25.389
There is another rare text
written about 100 years later

30:25.391 --> 30:28.892
that may be the key to unlocking
the secrets of Viking women.

30:31.831 --> 30:34.431
But this book is
very old.

30:34.433 --> 30:36.733
It's very fragile.

30:36.735 --> 30:38.435
[ Beeping ]

30:38.437 --> 30:40.003
FOX: It's not every day
you see a book

30:40.005 --> 30:42.406
with the same security
as the Hope Diamond...

30:45.344 --> 30:47.444
...but this book is priceless.

30:49.615 --> 30:52.382
This book,
written around 1,200 A.D.,

30:52.384 --> 30:54.818
is a detailed chronicle
of the history of the Danes

30:54.820 --> 30:56.553
called "Gesta Danorum"

30:56.555 --> 31:01.258
by the first-ever Danish
historian, Saxo Grammaticus.

31:01.260 --> 31:04.862
300 years later, this work would
inspire William Shakespeare

31:04.864 --> 31:07.464
to write "Hamlet."

31:07.466 --> 31:08.765
Wow.

31:08.767 --> 31:11.835
FOX: This is one of
the rarest books in the world.

31:11.837 --> 31:14.371
FOX: It's crazy because
it looks like

31:14.373 --> 31:16.306
when you think of,
like, Merlin,

31:16.308 --> 31:18.575
and it's right there,
and I can't touch it,

31:18.577 --> 31:20.043
but I'm very close
to touching it.

31:20.045 --> 31:22.412
I just have to take a picture.
It's crazy.

31:22.414 --> 31:24.348
That is really cool.
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

31:29.021 --> 31:30.487
"There were once
women in Denmark

31:30.489 --> 31:32.089
who dressed themselves
to look like men

31:32.091 --> 31:35.626
and spent almost every minute
cultivating soldier skills.

31:35.628 --> 31:37.861
They courted military expertise
so earnestly

31:37.863 --> 31:39.062
that anyone
would have guessed

31:39.064 --> 31:41.665
that they had
un-sexed themselves."
Yeah.

31:41.667 --> 31:44.468
"Those especially who had
forceful personalities" --

31:44.470 --> 31:46.436
<i> moi --</i>
"or were tall and elegant,

31:46.438 --> 31:48.972
tended to embark
on this way of life."
Right.

31:48.974 --> 31:51.008
"They put toughness
before allure,

31:51.010 --> 31:53.310
aimed at conflicts
instead of kisses,

31:53.312 --> 31:57.281
and desired not the couch
but the kill,

31:57.283 --> 32:00.617
and those they could have
appeased with looks

32:00.619 --> 32:02.986
they attacked with lances."

32:02.988 --> 32:06.590
-Yeah.
-That lights a fire in me.

32:07.526 --> 32:09.126
No, she's not --
that's just a woman.

32:09.128 --> 32:10.160
You think so?
Yeah. Okay.

32:10.162 --> 32:11.595
This is a man
that's afraid of a woman.

32:13.632 --> 32:15.165
They all died

32:15.167 --> 32:16.333
because they didn't
sit on the couch

32:16.335 --> 32:17.601
waiting for
those kisses.

32:17.603 --> 32:19.169
Right.

32:19.171 --> 32:21.271
It's frustrating
for me because,

32:21.273 --> 32:23.974
well, where is
the truth, then?

32:23.976 --> 32:26.209
What do we know
about history for sure?

32:29.248 --> 32:30.847
Well, what if we have
the source and now

32:30.849 --> 32:33.884
we're recovering bodies
in tombs

32:33.886 --> 32:35.619
that seem to be the tombs
of warriors,

32:35.621 --> 32:36.987
and they're female bodies?

32:43.762 --> 32:45.028
Mm-hmm.

32:45.030 --> 32:48.098
FOX: Viking graves,
Norse mythology,

32:48.100 --> 32:50.600
and now these texts
are challenging everything

32:50.602 --> 32:53.570
we thought we knew
about Viking women.

32:53.572 --> 32:56.173
But what's buried deep
in the British countryside

32:56.175 --> 32:59.543
could be the final piece
of the puzzle.

32:59.545 --> 33:03.213
Some of skeletons
from that mass grave...
Okay.

33:03.215 --> 33:04.614
...were actually women.

33:04.616 --> 33:05.849
Then there's
a very good chance

33:05.851 --> 33:08.852
that they were actually
actively involved in battle.

33:19.732 --> 33:21.331
FOX:
I've discovered Viking society

33:21.333 --> 33:23.666
was not the male-dominated
patriarchy

33:23.668 --> 33:26.636
our history books
had led us to believe.

33:26.638 --> 33:28.939
But did women fight
alongside men

33:28.941 --> 33:33.076
as warriors in the most feared
military force of its time?

33:33.078 --> 33:34.478
The answers could be at

33:34.480 --> 33:37.514
an active archeological
dig site in Repton, England.

33:37.516 --> 33:41.118
♪♪

33:41.120 --> 33:43.153
I love walking through
a graveyard.

33:43.155 --> 33:45.222
That's one of my favorite
things to do.
It is -- yeah.

33:45.224 --> 33:46.857
I used to always do this
when I was a child, as well.

33:46.859 --> 33:48.692
I'm being so sarcastic.
It's not --

33:48.694 --> 33:51.294
I'm so scared of energy
and spirts and all of that.

33:51.296 --> 33:53.897
Okay.
Fantastic.

33:53.899 --> 33:57.367
FOX: Archeologist Cat Jarman is
using state-of-the-art science

33:57.369 --> 33:59.903
to examine the largest
Viking mass grave

33:59.905 --> 34:02.139
ever discovered in England,

34:02.141 --> 34:04.641
located in the shadow
of this church.

34:04.643 --> 34:07.644
JARMAN: All these excavations
took place in the 1980s,

34:07.646 --> 34:09.413
and it's also where
I've been working

34:09.415 --> 34:11.715
for the last three years.

34:11.717 --> 34:13.617
FOX: Although the mass grave
was first discovered

34:13.619 --> 34:15.786
more than 35 years ago,

34:15.788 --> 34:17.554
no one has been able to say
for sure

34:17.556 --> 34:20.924
who these Vikings were
or why they died.

34:20.926 --> 34:24.194
But Cat might be the one
to finally change that.

34:24.196 --> 34:26.029
We have some new methods
and new techniques,

34:26.031 --> 34:29.733
and now with those new methods
we can find out stuff

34:29.735 --> 34:32.135
we couldn't find out
30 years ago.
Yeah.

34:32.137 --> 34:34.171
So, if you look at
the plan here,

34:34.173 --> 34:35.372
here's the mass grave.

34:35.374 --> 34:37.441
The mound is found
over here.

34:37.443 --> 34:39.810
JARMAN: So this is a photograph
from the excavations.

34:39.812 --> 34:42.345
So these are all femurs
or thigh bones.

34:42.347 --> 34:43.580
How many bodies?

34:43.582 --> 34:47.184
The minimum number of
individuals was 264 --

34:47.186 --> 34:49.886
at least 264 people
all in the same space.

34:49.888 --> 34:51.188
All right here.

34:51.190 --> 34:52.389
Yeah, right where
we're standing now.

34:52.391 --> 34:54.224
And no possessions,
no swords or --

34:54.226 --> 34:55.559
There were artifacts
there.

34:55.561 --> 34:57.094
Yeah, so there were
some artifacts,

34:57.096 --> 34:59.830
including an ax --
a Viking ax --

34:59.832 --> 35:03.300
and several other weapons
that were clearly Viking --

35:03.302 --> 35:04.634
various knives
and things.

35:04.636 --> 35:07.737
Oh, I love that.
That's exciting.

35:07.739 --> 35:10.640
FOX: Viking axes were a common
weapon of choice

35:10.642 --> 35:13.577
because they could be both
thrown from far distances

35:13.579 --> 35:16.913
or be swung during
hand-to-hand combat.

35:16.915 --> 35:20.117
Are you confident that
the burial site

35:20.119 --> 35:23.620
was related to a battle?

35:23.622 --> 35:26.356
JARMAN: So, we've been
looking at things like
how these people died.

35:26.358 --> 35:28.425
Many of them
do have injuries.

35:28.427 --> 35:29.926
They have evidence
of trauma.

35:29.928 --> 35:32.229
These were war dead.
These were battle dead.

35:32.231 --> 35:33.597
If they're buried
with weapons,

35:33.599 --> 35:34.965
if they have
all these injuries,

35:34.967 --> 35:36.166
then there's
a very good chance

35:36.168 --> 35:38.969
that they were actually
actively involved in battle.

35:38.971 --> 35:43.106
Does seem really likely that
it is Viking Great Army.
Yeah.

35:43.108 --> 35:46.409
FOX: These warriors likely died
here around 873 A.D.

35:46.411 --> 35:47.811
in an attempt by the Vikings

35:47.813 --> 35:50.180
to take land
from the Mercian dynasty,

35:50.182 --> 35:55.118
which controlled modern-day
England from 600 to 900 A.D.

35:55.120 --> 35:59.022
And with nearly 300
Viking bodies found so far,

35:59.024 --> 36:03.059
this must have been
one serious battle.

36:03.061 --> 36:05.729
But that's not even
the coolest part.

36:05.731 --> 36:08.231
Some of the skeletons
and some of the skulls

36:08.233 --> 36:10.967
from that mass grave
were actually women.

36:12.371 --> 36:14.604
FOX: Wow.
That's amazing.

36:14.606 --> 36:17.674
We can look at sex
from the skulls.

36:17.676 --> 36:20.343
So we look at things
like the brow,

36:20.345 --> 36:22.946
which is if they're
really defined.

36:22.948 --> 36:25.682
FOX: Archeologists often use
the size of a skull's brow

36:25.684 --> 36:27.284
to determine sex.

36:27.286 --> 36:30.387
Women have a smaller
and less pronounced brow line.

36:30.389 --> 36:32.055
FOX:
The brow ridge to me --

36:32.057 --> 36:33.790
Much smaller than
the other.
Smaller, yeah.

36:33.792 --> 36:35.091
-Yeah.
-Okay.

36:35.093 --> 36:37.794
So, this is
a female skull.

36:37.796 --> 36:39.529
Cool.

36:41.833 --> 36:44.234
That's a female skull.
It has to be.

36:44.236 --> 36:46.436
Yeah, this isn't
very pronounced.
It's just more delicate.

36:46.438 --> 36:48.705
You can see a pretty big
difference in the skulls.
Yeah.

36:48.707 --> 36:50.073
-Yeah.
-Exactly.

36:50.075 --> 36:53.343
Where we could determine
what sex an individual was,

36:53.345 --> 36:56.112
20% were actually women.

36:56.114 --> 36:57.514
Yeah.

36:57.516 --> 37:00.383
If this is a burial site
from a battle

37:00.385 --> 37:03.253
and they were all injured
or killed in war,

37:03.255 --> 37:05.488
and 20% of them
are female,

37:05.490 --> 37:09.025
the implications would be
the warriors were female.

37:09.027 --> 37:11.261
-Yeah.
-That's very exciting.

37:11.263 --> 37:14.998
And that's blowing
a story wide open.
Yeah.

37:15.000 --> 37:16.866
FOX:
This is incredible.

37:16.868 --> 37:19.336
We aren't talking about
a single instance

37:19.338 --> 37:23.573
of a powerful woman or a lone
female warrior's grave.

37:23.575 --> 37:25.609
Now we have hundreds
of Viking warriors,

37:25.611 --> 37:28.311
and many among them are women.

37:28.313 --> 37:30.013
This changes everything.

37:30.015 --> 37:33.350
♪♪

37:41.293 --> 37:46.296
♪♪

37:46.298 --> 37:49.566
FOX: If this a burial site
from a battle,

37:49.568 --> 37:51.568
and 20% of them
are female,

37:51.570 --> 37:53.103
the warriors were female.

37:53.105 --> 37:54.671
Yeah, then there's
a very good chance

37:54.673 --> 37:58.642
that they were actually
actively involved in battle.

37:58.644 --> 38:00.443
That's very exciting.

38:02.180 --> 38:05.248
FOX: Human remains in a Viking
mass grave in Repton, England,

38:05.250 --> 38:07.884
have provided archeologist
Cat Jarman

38:07.886 --> 38:09.986
with shocking evidence.

38:09.988 --> 38:11.354
1,100 years ago,

38:11.356 --> 38:14.858
a squadron of Viking soldiers
fought and died here,

38:14.860 --> 38:18.762
and many of them were women.

38:18.764 --> 38:22.065
That's blowing
a story wide open.
Yeah.

38:22.067 --> 38:24.601
FOX: But what was
this squad's mission?

38:24.603 --> 38:27.904
Were women an integral part
of the Viking war machine?

38:27.906 --> 38:29.839
Or would they have been sent
to the slaughter

38:29.841 --> 38:33.943
because they weren't actually
respected warriors at all?

38:33.945 --> 38:37.280
The answer could lie in the
bowels of St. Wystan's Church,

38:37.282 --> 38:40.383
located just feet
from the Viking mass grave.

38:40.385 --> 38:42.719
So, this church
is quite special.

38:42.721 --> 38:44.187
So, there is actually
a part of this church

38:44.189 --> 38:46.723
that dates right back
when the Vikings were here.

38:46.725 --> 38:54.297
♪♪

38:54.299 --> 38:56.599
Although this church was
rebuilt 400 years

38:56.601 --> 38:59.602
after the Vikings
would have fought here,

38:59.604 --> 39:01.104
two stories below are remnants

39:01.106 --> 39:04.274
of what these Viking warriors
might have been after.

39:04.276 --> 39:06.843
♪♪

39:06.845 --> 39:09.245
This is really the only
original part,

39:09.247 --> 39:10.647
which was what
would have been there

39:10.649 --> 39:12.282
when the Vikings
were here.
FOX: Okay.

39:12.284 --> 39:16.119
And this dates back to
about 700 or 800 A.D.

39:16.121 --> 39:19.556
So it's quite dark down there,
so a torch for you.

39:19.558 --> 39:20.957
You take that one.
Should I be nervous?

39:20.959 --> 39:23.660
-No, no, absolutely not.
-[ Laughing ] Okay.

39:23.662 --> 39:26.796
Quite steep steps,
so just take care,
and we'll go down.

39:26.798 --> 39:30.734
♪♪

39:30.736 --> 39:33.269
So this is the crypt.

39:33.271 --> 39:37.240
♪♪

39:37.242 --> 39:38.842
Okay.

39:38.844 --> 39:42.178
♪♪

39:42.180 --> 39:43.813
This is a really
important place.

39:43.815 --> 39:46.349
This was where a lot of
the kings were buried.

39:46.351 --> 39:48.017
It was very wealthy.

39:48.019 --> 39:50.353
FOX: Ancient crypts guarded
the remains and possessions

39:50.355 --> 39:52.922
of the most important people
of their day.

39:52.924 --> 39:54.691
This crypt contained
the grave goods

39:54.693 --> 39:57.260
of powerful Mercian kings
who controlled

39:57.262 --> 39:58.895
what is now modern-day England

39:58.897 --> 40:01.831
when the Vikings attacked
this church.

40:01.833 --> 40:05.668
These pillars date back
about 1,300 years.

40:05.670 --> 40:07.470
A lot of this is
exactly the way it was

40:07.472 --> 40:09.439
when the Vikings attacked.

40:09.441 --> 40:15.779
♪♪

40:15.781 --> 40:17.781
I've never been
in a crypt before.

40:19.885 --> 40:21.117
Do you like it?

40:21.119 --> 40:23.686
[ Laughing ]
I don't hate it.

40:23.688 --> 40:26.256
But I wouldn't want to stay here
for very long, though,

40:26.258 --> 40:28.858
and I wouldn't want
this torch to die out.

40:28.860 --> 40:32.328
♪♪

40:32.330 --> 40:34.831
FOX: This crypt would have
likely housed priceless riches

40:34.833 --> 40:37.167
with a value
that we can only guess.

40:37.169 --> 40:39.836
They assumed that
there would be

40:39.838 --> 40:43.506
treasure of sorts here,
as well...
Yeah, definitely.

40:43.508 --> 40:44.474
...gold and so forth?

40:44.476 --> 40:45.809
Yeah, all sorts of
treasure.

40:45.811 --> 40:48.445
And we know that because
the archeological excavations

40:48.447 --> 40:50.180
have found some items
of treasure --

40:50.182 --> 40:51.681
really precious
bits of jewelry,

40:51.683 --> 40:52.982
really nice glass.

40:52.984 --> 40:54.250
We know this was
really wealthy,

40:54.252 --> 40:56.085
so that's exactly
the sort of thing

40:56.087 --> 40:57.887
that the Vikings
were looking for.

41:00.125 --> 41:03.126
So taking over this is
a really powerful thing.

41:04.896 --> 41:07.197
We've all seen
"Braveheart."

41:07.199 --> 41:10.767
What I picture in my mind
is just, like, a ruthless,

41:10.769 --> 41:15.505
bloody pillaging of everything
and everyone that was here,

41:15.507 --> 41:17.073
and then we're standing
right here

41:17.075 --> 41:18.675
where that took place.

41:18.677 --> 41:20.910
And the idea that
they were female

41:20.912 --> 41:22.979
and they were
female warriors --

41:22.981 --> 41:26.549
that opens up
a lot of new things.

41:26.551 --> 41:28.251
FOX: This crypt likely
would have been

41:28.253 --> 41:31.120
an extremely high-value target
for the Vikings,

41:31.122 --> 41:32.989
and capturing it
would have required

41:32.991 --> 41:35.358
exceptionally skilled soldiers,

41:35.360 --> 41:38.294
like a Viking SEAL Team 6.

41:38.296 --> 41:41.197
And some of these
highly skilled warriors

41:41.199 --> 41:42.866
appear to have been women.

41:42.868 --> 41:46.269
♪♪

41:46.271 --> 41:47.637
They were here,

41:47.639 --> 41:51.708
standing in the footsteps
of a lot of history.

41:51.710 --> 41:53.576
History books have said
that Viking women

41:53.578 --> 41:57.213
only adhered to conventional
gender stereotypes.

41:57.215 --> 41:59.916
But that is dead wrong.

41:59.918 --> 42:03.086
♪♪

42:03.088 --> 42:06.189
Human history
is not written in stone.

42:06.191 --> 42:08.491
Just like our understanding
of the Vikings,

42:08.493 --> 42:11.227
it's always evolving.

42:11.229 --> 42:14.063
With just one
profound discovery,

42:14.065 --> 42:17.000
mankind's entire story
could change.

42:17.002 --> 42:19.502
♪♪

42:19.504 --> 42:23.006
So, if we're ever going to
unlock the secrets of the past,

42:23.008 --> 42:25.475
we need to be open
to change with it.

42:25.477 --> 42:28.545
♪♪
